<h1 id="1.-Linear-Regression">1. Linear Regression<a class="anchor-link" href="#1.-Linear-Regression">¶</a></h1><p>Consider a linear regression.</p>
<p>$$\text{Given} \; \begin{cases}
x_{i} \; \text{: inputs} \\
y_{i} \; \text{: outputs}
\end{cases}$$
, Find $$\theta_{0}$$ and $$\theta_{1}$$</p>
$$x=
\begin{bmatrix}
x_{1} \\
x_{2} \\
\vdots \\
x_{m}
\end{bmatrix}, \qquad
y=
\begin{bmatrix}
y_{1} \\
y_{2} \\
\vdots \\
y_{m}
\end{bmatrix} \approx
\hat{y}_{i} = \theta_{0} + \theta_{1}x_{i}$$<ul>
<li><p>$$ \hat{y}_{i} $$ : predicted output</p>
</li>
<li><p>$$ \theta =
\begin{bmatrix}
\theta_{0} \\
\theta_{1} \\
\end{bmatrix}
$$ : Model parameters</p>
</li>
</ul>
$$ \hat{y}_{i} = f(x_{i}\,; \theta) \; \text{ in general}$$<ul>
<li>in many cases, a linear model is used to predict $$y_{i}$$</li>
</ul>
$$ \hat{y}_{i} = \theta_{0} + \theta_{1}x_{i} \; \quad \text{  such that  }\quad  \min\limits_{\theta_{0}, \theta_{1}}\sum\limits_{i = 1}^{m} (\hat{y}_{i} - y_{i})^2$$



<p><br/><br/></p>
<center><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="400"/></center>

<h2 id="1.1.-Re-cast-Problem-as-a-Least-Squares">1.1. Re-cast Problem as a Least Squares<a class="anchor-link" href="#1.1.-Re-cast-Problem-as-a-Least-Squares">¶</a></h2><ul>
<li>For convenience, we define a function that maps inputs to feature vectors, $$\phi$$</li>
</ul>
<p><br/>
$$\begin{array}{Icr}\begin{align*} \hat{y}_{i}
 = \theta_0 + x_i \theta_1 = 1 \cdot \theta_0 + x_i \theta_1 \\ \\
 = \begin{bmatrix}1 \ \ x_{i}\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\theta_{0} \\ \theta_{1}\end{bmatrix} \\\\
 =\begin{bmatrix}1 \\ x_{i} \end{bmatrix}^{T}\begin{bmatrix}\theta_{0} \\ \theta_{1}\end{bmatrix} \\\\
 =\phi^{T}(x_{i})\ \theta
\end{align*}\end{array}
\begin{array}{Icr}
\quad \quad  \text{where feature vector}
\; \phi(x_{i}) = \begin{bmatrix}1 \\ x_{i}\end{bmatrix}
\end{array}$$</p>
<p><br/></p>
$$\Phi = \begin{bmatrix}1 \ \ x_{1} \\ 1 \ \ x_{2} \\ \vdots \\1 \ \ x_{m} \end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}\phi^T(x_{1}) \\\phi^T(x_{2}) \\\vdots \\\phi^T(x_{m}) \end{bmatrix} \quad \implies \quad \hat{y} = \begin{bmatrix}\hat{y}_{1} \\\hat{y}_{2} \\\vdots \\\hat{y}_{m}\end{bmatrix}=\Phi\theta$$<p><br/></p>
<ul>
<li>Optimization problem
<br/></li>
</ul>
$$\min\limits_{\theta_{0}, \theta_{1}}\sum\limits_{i = 1}^{m} (\hat{y}_{i} - y_{i})^2
=\min\limits_{\theta}\lVert\Phi\theta-y\rVert^2_2
\qquad \qquad  \left(\text{same as} \; \min_{x} \lVert Ax-b \rVert_2^2 \right)$$<p><br/><br/>
$$ \text{solution} \;
\theta^* = (\Phi^{T}\Phi)^{-1}\Phi^{T} y
$$</p>

<p><strong>Note</strong></p>
<p><br/><br/></p>
<p></p><center><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="400"/></center>
<br/>
$$\begin{array}{Icr} \text{input} \\ x_{i} \end{array}
\quad \rightarrow \quad
\begin{array}{Icr} \text{feature} \\ \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ x_{i} \end{bmatrix} \end{array}
\quad \rightarrow \quad
\begin{array}{Icr} \text{predicted output} \\ \hat{y}_{i} \end{array}$$<p><br/></p>
$$\begin{array}{Icr}
\begin{bmatrix} 1 \ \ x_{1} \\1 \ \ x_{2}\\\vdots \ \ \vdots\\1 \ \ x_{m}\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\theta_0\\\theta_1\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}y_{1} \\y_{2} \\\vdots \\y_{m}\end{bmatrix} \\
\begin{array}{Icr} \uparrow \\ \vec{A}_1 \end{array}
\;\;
\begin{array}{Icr} \uparrow \\ \vec{A}_2 \end{array}
\quad
\begin{array}{Icr} \uparrow \\ \vec{x} \end{array}
\quad\quad \;\;
\begin{array}{Icr} \uparrow \\ \vec{B} \end{array}
\end{array}
\quad
\begin{array}{Icr}
\quad \text{over-determined or} \\
\quad \text{projection}
\end{array}$$<p><br/></p>
$$A(= \Phi) = \left[ \vec{A}_1 \;\vec{A}_2 \right]$$

<h3 id="1.2.2.-Use-Gradient-Descent">1.2.2. Use Gradient Descent<a class="anchor-link" href="#1.2.2.-Use-Gradient-Descent">¶</a></h3><p><br/><br/>
$$\min_{\theta} ~ \lVert \hat y - y \rVert_2^2  =  \min_{\theta} ~ \lVert A\theta - y \rVert_2^2$$</p>
<p><br/><br/>
$$
\begin{align*}
f = (A\theta-y)^T(A\theta-y) = (\theta^TA^T-y^T)(A\theta-y) \\
= \theta^TA^TA\theta - \theta^TA^Ty - y^TA\theta + y^Ty \\\\
\nabla f = A^TA\theta + A^TA\theta - A^Ty - A^Ty = 2(A^TA\theta - A^Ty)
\end{align*}
$$</p>
<p><br/>
$$
\theta \leftarrow \theta - \alpha \nabla f
$$</p>

```python
theta = np.random.randn(2,1)
theta = np.asmatrix(theta)

alpha = 0.001

for _ in range(1000):
    df = 2*(A.T@A@theta - A.T@y)
    # NOTE: @ is matrix multiplication
    theta = theta - alpha*df

print (theta)
```
    [[0.65279979]
     [0.67137543]]

<h3 id="1.2.3.-Use-CVXPY-Optimization">1.2.3. Use CVXPY Optimization<a class="anchor-link" href="#1.2.3.-Use-CVXPY-Optimization">¶</a></h3><p><br/><br/>
$$\min_{\theta} ~ \lVert \hat y - y \rVert_2  =  \min_{\theta} ~ \lVert A\theta - y \rVert_2$$</p>

```python
import cvxpy as cvx

theta2 = cvx.Variable([2, 1])

obj = cvx.Minimize(cvx.norm(A@theta2 - y, 2))
# NOTE: @ is matrix multiplication
cvx.Problem(obj,[]).solve()

print('theta2:\n', theta2.value)
```
    theta2:
     [[0.65306531]
     [0.67129519]]

<p><font size="4"><b>By the way, do we have to use only $$L_2$$ norm? No.</b></font></p>
<ul>
<li>Let's use $$L_1$$ norm</li>
</ul>
<p><br/><br/>
$$  \min_{\theta} ~ \lVert \hat y - y \rVert_1  =  \min_{\theta} ~ \lVert A\theta - y \rVert_1  $$</p>

```python
theta1 = cvx.Variable([2, 1])
obj = cvx.Minimize(cvx.norm(A@theta1-y, 1))
# NOTE: @ is matrix multiplication
cvx.Problem(obj).solve()

print('theta1:\n', theta1.value)
```

<h1 id="2.-Multivariate-Linear-Regression">2. Multivariate Linear Regression<a class="anchor-link" href="#2.-Multivariate-Linear-Regression">¶</a></h1><p>(= linear regression for multivariate data)</p>
<p><br/></p>
$$ \hat{y} = \theta_0 + \theta_{1}x_1 + \theta_{2}x_2  $$<p>$$$$ $$$$</p>
$$\phi \left(x^{(i)}\right) = \begin{bmatrix}1\\x^{(i)}_{1}\\x^{(i)}_{2} \end{bmatrix}$$<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="300"/></p>



```python

# for 3D plot
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D


```


```python

# y = theta0 + theta1*x1 + theta2*x2 + noise

n = 200
x1 = np.random.randn(n, 1)
x2 = np.random.randn(n, 1)
noise = 0.5*np.random.randn(n, 1);

y = 2 + 1*x1 + 3*x2 + noise

fig = plt.figure(figsize = (10, 8))
ax = fig.add_subplot(1, 1, 1, projection = '3d')
ax.set_title('Generated Data', fontsize = 15)
ax.set_xlabel('$$X_1$$', fontsize = 15)
ax.set_ylabel('$$X_2$$', fontsize = 15)
ax.set_zlabel('Y', fontsize = 15)
ax.scatter(x1, x2, y, marker = '.', label = 'Data')
#ax.view_init(30,30)
plt.legend(fontsize = 15)
plt.show()
```

![png](/assets/images/regression1/output_38_0.png){:height="800px" width="700px"}


<p><br/></p>
$$\Phi = \begin{bmatrix}1 \ x_{1}^{(1)} \ x_{2}^{(1)}\\1 \ x_{1}^{(2)} \ x_{2}^{(2)}\\ \vdots \\1 \ x_{1}^{(m)} \ x_{2}^{(m)} \end{bmatrix} \quad \implies \quad \hat{y} = \begin{bmatrix}\hat{y}^{(1)} \\\hat{y}^{(2)} \\\vdots \\\hat{y}^{(m)}\end{bmatrix}=\Phi\theta$$<p><br/><br/></p>
$$\implies \theta^{*} = (\Phi^T \Phi)^{-1} \Phi^T y$$



```python

#% matplotlib qt5

A = np.hstack([np.ones((n, 1)), x1, x2])
A = np.asmatrix(A)
theta = (A.T*A).I*A.T*y

X1, X2 = np.meshgrid(np.arange(np.min(x1), np.max(x1), 0.5),
                     np.arange(np.min(x2), np.max(x2), 0.5))
YP = theta[0,0] + theta[1,0]*X1 + theta[2,0]*X2

fig = plt.figure(figsize = (10, 8))
ax = fig.add_subplot(1, 1, 1, projection = '3d')
ax.set_title('Regression', fontsize = 15)
ax.set_xlabel('$$X_1$$', fontsize = 15)
ax.set_ylabel('$$X_2$$', fontsize = 15)
ax.set_zlabel('Y', fontsize = 15)
ax.scatter(x1, x2, y, marker = '.', label = 'Data')
ax.plot_wireframe(X1, X2, YP, color = 'k', alpha = 0.3, label = 'Regression Plane')
#ax.view_init(30,30)
plt.legend(fontsize = 15)
plt.show()


```

<h1 id="3.-Nonlinear-Regression">3. Nonlinear Regression<a class="anchor-link" href="#3.-Nonlinear-Regression">¶</a></h1><p>(= Linear Regression for Non-linear Data)</p>

<center><img align="center" src="data:image/png;base64," width="300"/></center><ul>

</ul>
<ul>
<li>Method 1: constructing explicit feature vectors<ul>

</ul>
</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="3.1.-Nonlinear-Regression-with-Polynomial-Features">3.1. Nonlinear Regression with Polynomial Features<a class="anchor-link" href="#3.1.-Nonlinear-Regression-with-Polynomial-Features">¶</a></h2><p>(here, quad is used as an example)</p>
<p><br/>
$$
\begin{align*}
y = \theta_0 + \theta_1 x + \theta_2 x^2 + \text{noise}
\end{align*}
$$</p>
<p><br/><br/>
$$\phi(x_{i}) =  \begin{bmatrix}1\\x_{i}\\x_{i}^2 \end{bmatrix}$$</p>



$$\Phi = \begin{bmatrix}1 \ x_{1} \ x_{1}^2 \\ 1 \  x_{2} \ x_{2}^2 \\ \vdots \\ 1 \ x_{m} \ x_{m}^2\end{bmatrix} \quad \implies \quad \hat{y} = \begin{bmatrix}\hat{y}_1 \\\hat{y}_2 \\\vdots \\\hat{y}_m\end{bmatrix}=\Phi\theta$$<p><br/><br/></p>
$$\implies \theta^{*} = (\Phi^T \Phi)^{-1} \Phi^T y$$



```python

# y = theta0 + theta1*x + theta2*x^2 + noise

n = 100            
x = -5 + 15*np.random.rand(n, 1)
noise = 10*np.random.randn(n, 1)

y = 10 + 1*x + 2*x**2 + noise

plt.figure(figsize = (10, 8))
plt.title('True x and y', fontsize = 15)
plt.xlabel('X', fontsize = 15)
plt.ylabel('Y', fontsize = 15)
plt.plot(x, y, 'o', markersize = 4, label = 'actual')
plt.xlim([np.min(x), np.max(x)])
plt.grid(alpha = 0.3)
plt.legend(fontsize = 15)
plt.show()


```

```python

A = np.hstack([x**0, x, x**2])
A = np.asmatrix(A)

theta = (A.T@A).I@A.T@y
print('theta:\n', theta)


```

```python

xp = np.linspace(np.min(x), np.max(x))
yp = theta[0,0] + theta[1,0]*xp + theta[2,0]*xp**2

plt.figure(figsize = (10, 8))
plt.plot(x, y, 'o', markersize = 4, label = 'actual')
plt.plot(xp, yp, 'r', linewidth = 2, label = 'estimated')

plt.title('Nonlinear regression', fontsize = 15)
plt.xlabel('X', fontsize = 15)
plt.ylabel('Y', fontsize = 15)
plt.xlim([np.min(x), np.max(x)])
plt.grid(alpha = 0.3)
plt.legend(fontsize = 15)
```
